CH9

When our wickedness had reached its height, and it had been clearly shown that its reward was punishment and death, and the time came which God had ordained to manifest His goodness and power, He did not hate us or reject us or remember our evils. Instead, He showed patience and bore with us, and in pity took our sins upon Himself. He gave His own Son as a ransom for us — the Holy for the unholy, the Innocent for the wicked, the Righteous for the unrighteous, the Incorruptible for the corruptible, the Immortal for the mortal.
For what else could cover our sins but His righteousness? In whom was it possible for us, the lawless and ungodly, to be justified except in the Son of God alone?
God showed forth His own love toward us, not that we loved Him, but that He loved us and sent His Son to be the propitiation for our sins.
When our unrighteousness was fulfilled and it had been made manifest that its wages were punishment and death, then the season arrived in which God determined to reveal at last His goodness and power.

