This is He who is from the beginning, who appeared new and was found to be old, and is always being born young in the hearts of the saints.
This is the Word who is from God, through whom all things were made, and without whom nothing was made that has been made. This is the Savior and Redeemer, the Creator and Fashioner, the true God.
The Christians have found the truth. For they do not worship the works of men’s hands, nor do they sacrifice to senseless idols, nor do they observe the superstitions of the Jews.

CH7

He sent Him as a Savior, not as a judge; as a God of mercy, not of terror. He sent Him in gentleness and meekness, not in anger or violence. For He did not send Him to terrify us, but to persuade us by love.
For God, the Master and Creator of the universe, who made all things and set them in order, showed Himself not only loving toward mankind, but also long-suffering. He sent His only-begotten Son into the world, not to condemn the world, but that the world through Him might be saved.
He sent Him as King, as God, as Man, as Savior, as the Way, as the Door, as the Life, as the Truth. He sent the Fashioner and Maker of all things to men in the world, not to exercise tyranny or to instill fear, but in gentleness and meekness.
This is He who was from the beginning, who appeared new and was found to be old, and is always being born young in the hearts of the saints. This is the eternal Word, who was from the beginning, who is now made known, and who is to come.

CH6

The soul is immortal and dwells in a mortal tabernacle. So also Christians dwell in the world as strangers, yet they sustain the world. The soul is enclosed in the body, yet it holds the body together. So Christians are confined in the world as in a prison, yet they hold the world together. The soul, though invisible, is manifest in the body. So Christians are in the world, yet their godliness remains invisible. The soul is hated by the flesh, yet it loves the flesh that hates it. So Christians are hated by the world, yet they love those who hate them.
What the soul is in the body, Christians are in the world. The soul is spread throughout all the members of the body, and Christians are spread throughout all the cities of the world. The soul dwells in the body, yet it is not of the body. So Christians dwell in the world, yet they are not of the world. The soul is invisible and is guarded in a visible body. So Christians are known to be in the world, yet their worship of God remains invisible.

CH5

They are in the flesh, but they do not live according to the flesh. They pass their days on earth, but they are citizens of heaven. They obey the prescribed laws, and at the same time surpass the laws by their lives. They love all men, and are persecuted by all. They are unknown, and yet they are condemned. They are put to death, and yet they are brought to life. They are poor, yet they make many rich. They are in lack of all things, and yet they abound in all things. They are dishonored, and yet in their very dishonor they are glorified. They are spoken evil of, and yet they are vindicated. They are reviled, and they bless. They are insulted, and they repay the insult with honor. They do good, and are punished as evil-doers. When punished, they rejoice as if quickened into life. They are assailed as foreigners, and yet they pacify the world. They are poor, and yet they enrich many. They are in lack of all things, and yet they abound in all.
What the soul is in the body, that Christians are in the world.

CH4

But as for their scruples about meats, and their superstition about the Sabbath, and their boasting about circumcision, and their hypocrisy about fasting and new moons — I do not think it is necessary to teach you that these things are worthless and not a true service to God. For if they truly understood the will of YHWH, they would not observe these external things which profit nothing.
For the Jews, supposing that they alone know the true God, do not understand that they worship Him no better than the Gentiles who offer the same sacrifices. For what is the difference between those who think they are offering to God and those who offer to idols, if both are ignorant of the true nature of God?
The Jews, then, if they abstain from certain foods and observe the Sabbath and practice circumcision, think they are offering a special service to God. But these practices are no different from the superstitions of the Gentiles.

