CH2

They worship the works of men’s hands, calling them gods. They sacrifice to senseless idols, and yet they call themselves wise. They fear the things they themselves have made, and yet they mock those who do not worship them.
The Christians do not worship the same gods as the Greeks, nor do they observe the superstitions of the Jews. They do not sacrifice to idols, nor do they keep the Jewish customs of meats, Sabbaths, and circumcision.
For the gods of the Greeks are made of stone, wood, silver, or gold, and are the work of human hands. They have mouths but do not speak, eyes but do not see, ears but do not hear. They have hands but do not feel, feet but do not walk. Those who make them and those who trust in them are like them.
The Jews worship the one God, but they worship Him in a carnal way, observing external rites and ceremonies that do not reach the heart.

CH1

Since you have shown such eagerness to learn about the Christian way of life, I gladly undertake to explain it to you. For I see that you are most sincerely seeking to understand what God it is that Christians worship, and what manner of life they follow that sets them apart from the rest of mankind.
You have asked me, most excellent Diognetus, what God Christians worship and what is the secret of their love for one another, and why this new race or way of life has appeared in the world now and not before.
I rejoice that you have such a desire, and I pray that God, who has made all things and given us all things, will grant me the grace to speak rightly and that you may be found worthy to receive the truth.
